Bay Area Bike Sharing Trips

Anonymized bike trip data from Jan 2019 to March 2019

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) by Kevin Francisco Chacón Vargas, September 2020

Context


The individualized mobility projects, in this case bycicles, have been growing in the last 10 years, as an alternative and solution to traffic congestion and environmental pollution. As DeMaio (2020) points in his blog, the growth of this type of projects has gone from one every couple of weeks to one each day. Fact that denotes that bike-sharing is a low-cost alternative (compared to other models of transportation) and both the public and private sectors can have great benefits from its implementation.

For these reasons, the following notebook presents an Exploratory Data Analysis of the Bay Area from January 2019 to March 2019 as an introduction to the matter of bike-sharing and some interesting facts that the data analyzed denotes.

Objectives


General objective:

Elaborate an Exploratory Data Analysis of the Bay Area dataset from January 2019 to March 2019 to find insights that suggest the distribution and behaviour of the use of bike-sharing.


Specific objetives:

  • Perform a cleansing and transformation of the data prior to its analysis.
  • Use the Pandas, Numpy, Matplotlib and Seaborn packages to normalize, map and visualize the information.
  • Compute mathematical operations to understand the behaviour of data.
  • Generate conclusions and suggestions about the data.

    • Section #1: About the dataset


    The files are available at: https://www.kaggle.com/jolasa/bay-area-bike-sharing-trips

    Section #2: Data Cleansing Process


    A very crucial step of the data preparation is the process of identifying and correcting messy and raw data. In the case of the dataset that is been analyzed all the attributes presented are useful for get insights and there are just two little issues with them: NaN values and (probably) values without any sense in the member_birth_year column.

    To solve this, lets start seeing how many of NaN values exist in each attribute.

    As can be seen, the NaN values exist in two kind of categories of attributes. One that has information about the stations and another one that has data about the users. For an adequate treatment, lets divide its cleansing in two parts. In this sense, we can avoid any misunderstanding of the data and how it must be treated.

    Lets start with the attributes that have information about the users.

    member_birth_year

    As there is no other attribute where we can infer the birth_year of the user, lets see what is the range of years that the dataset has. With this, we will know if there are years that does not make any sense (e.g. 1800, etc.) and also, lets establish a year for the NaN values that does not create any bias over the other data.

    In [7]:
    by_min= df["member_birth_year"].min()
by_max= df["member_birth_year"].max()
list([by_min,by_max])
    Out[7]:
    [1878.0, 2001.0]

    As it was supposed, the attribute has a set of birth years that couldn't be possible. This issue is common due to the user can create an account in the app and as part of the registration form has to define a birth year. This value is selected with a dropdown list or calendar and most applications do not have any restrictions for the values that are presented to the user.

    Now, the information that gives us this column help us to define a consumer profile (based on its age). For this reason, as a first step lets compute what is the percentage of values that are NaN and the ones that (probably) does not have any sense. This will alert us if the percentages are significant or not. Then, lets assign a value of 0 to the NaN cases.

    In [8]:
    nan_cases_percentage = (df["member_birth_year"].isnull().sum() / df["member_birth_year"].count()) * 100

print("Percentage of NaN values in member_birth_year: ", round(nan_cases_percentage,2),"%")

    Percentage of NaN values in member_birth_year:  4.93 %
    In [9]:
    #Lets assume that 100 years old is the maximum age that is considered to ride a bike
outliers_cases = df[df.member_birth_year < 1919] 

outliers_cases_percentage = (outliers_cases["member_birth_year"].count() / df["member_birth_year"].count()) * 100
print("Percentage of outlier values (+100 years old users) in member_birth_year: ",
      round(outliers_cases_percentage,2),"%")

    Percentage of outlier values (+100 years old users) in member_birth_year:  0.05 %
    In [10]:
    #Assing a zero-value to NaN cases
df["member_birth_year"].fillna(0, inplace=True)

    member_gender

    The member gender is a very important value to create a profile of our target. However, it is known that some people prefer to not specify its gender as "male" or "female". The analysis of its reason is not the focus of this EDA, therefore, for the moment lets change the NaN value for a "Not defined".

    In [11]:
    df["member_gender"] = df["member_gender"].replace(np.nan, "Not defined", regex=True)

    Having done the attributes that refer to information about the users, lets focus on the columns that have data about the stations.

    start_station_id || start_station_name || end_station_id || end_station_name

    Giving an hypothesis about the missed data here and since the bikes are the ones that should receive/communicate the place where they are each time they arrive to a station, it seems that the problem comes from the sensors of the bikes. Trying to map the problem in an ease way, lets imgine that when the bike arrives to the station "A" there is a communication between the station and the bike that registers the id_station to the bike. In this sense, the bike can create a record of its trips everytime it leaves and arrives to a station.

    Taking the previous explanation as a possible one, lets create a filtered dataset to validate if the problem is focused in some bikes.

    Section #3: Data Exploration and Visualization


    According to the information that we have in our dataset, lets navigate our analysis in two parts:

    1) Understanding the use of the bikes and the environment: This part is focused in the understanding of some general distributions of the data, the average trip duration and what are the most important factor to consider in order to gain clarity about the behaviour of the users.

    2) Consumer profile, trends and strategies: Here, the analysis is focused in the creation of a consumer profile based on its demographic information and also, what seems to be the trends that can be deduce along the three months in study.

    Specifically, lets answer the following questions:

    • What's the average trip duration, in minutes?
    • What's the service member age distribution? Are there significant behavioral differences between age groups?
    • Are there any significant differences between subscribed and non-suscribed service members?
    • Are there any significant differences in service use throughout time?
    • What are the most used (top 10) stations for trip beginning and/or endings? Highlight behavior associated with these stations.

    Understanding the use of the bikes and the environment


    To begin, lets normalize the attribute "trip_duration_sec" to show it in minutes.

    In [25]:
    df["trip_duration_min"] = round(df["trip_duration_sec"] / 60,2)
df = df.drop("trip_duration_sec", axis=1)

    Now, lets understand the distribution of the time that the users are in the bikes. As it is shown in the following series, the mean time of riding a bike is 12.78 min and the 75% of all users spend as long as 13.78min riding.

    This fact is important because gives us a glance about the distances that the users are doing with regularity. However, it is also interesting that the maximum time of a trip has been approx. 1428 min (59.5 days). At first view this amount of time can be thought as an outlier, however, lets validate if a significant portion of the uses are in this scale of minutes. To do this, lets compute the 99.5th percentile that cover most of our data.

    The plot shows that one of the most visited (used) stations is San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 (Townsend St at 4th St) due to it is a major transit hub in the area. As its website cited, this station covers 6 principal zones and,in a regular weekday more than 7.000 Caltrain's users ride a bike to its stations. In proportion, that means that approximately a 10% of the total visitors of Caltrain in a regular working-day are using this mode of transportation. Another example of one of the most used stations is Market St at 10th St in Philadelphia and that is because it is a bus station. According to the United States Census Bureau, in 2019 were 1,584,064 people living in this county. That explains why having a low-cost and healthy alternative as the bike-sharing is a growing trend on those places.

    According to the previous references, we now know that the reason behind why these 10 stations are the most popular is because they are bus/train stations or hubs to other types of transportation.

    Another important fact that must be taken into account is if there exist differences in the use of the bikes depending on the month. To analyze this, lets group the information month by month and also lets see the relation with each of the top stations.

    To begin, lets see the trend of the use of bikes along the three months and validate if the climate could affect in the behaviour that is seen.

    Something interesting to note is that the minimum age of the users is 18 years old. This fact is according to the norm in the use of this kind of applications, payments, and insurances. At the same time, the 95% of the users are between 18 and 71 years old, placing themselves as Generation Z, Millenials, Generation X (and some Baby Boomers). This fact, along with the data presented by Pew Research Center (2019) about the adoption of technology that each generation has, supports the incremental trend in the use of bikes showed in previous charts. According to Pew, 73% of online Millenials (the ones that use internet services, smarthphones and apps in a regular basis) evaluates the internet as a good thing. This, coupled with the fact that ride a bike protects the environment, it is low-cost and it is healthy, convert this alternative to one with the biggest increment in popularity in the last years.

    The previous chart presents information about the adoption of technology of each generation. Likewise, tell us that Millenials are the ones born from 1981 to 1996. Acoording to this, lets compute what are the percentage of users in each generation.

    In [52]:
    #Calculating the percentages
silent = round(((df_95["member_birth_year"] <= 1946).sum())/df_95["member_birth_year"].count()*100,2)

baby_boomers = round((((df_95["member_birth_year"] > 1946) & 
                 (df_95["member_birth_year"] <= 1964)).sum())/df_95["member_birth_year"].count()*100,2)

gen_x = round((((df_95["member_birth_year"] > 1964) & (df_95["member_birth_year"] <= 1980)).sum())/df_95["member_birth_year"].count()*100,2)

millenials = round((((df_95["member_birth_year"] > 1980) & (df_95["member_birth_year"] <= 1996)).sum())/df_95["member_birth_year"].count()*100,2)

gen_z = round((((df_95["member_birth_year"] > 1996)).sum())/df_95["member_birth_year"].count()*100,2)

#Creating a dict with the results

    Likewise, as Taine (2017) denotes it his blog, the Millenials are a generation of early-adopters and since the application was created in 2012, the adoption curve has been really fast.

    To put it in detail, the vast majority of the users that are in the 95th percentile of the dataset belongs to the generation called "Millennials". Into this generation the behaviour of a significant portion of the people (referring to the adoption of technology) is described as "Early adopters". Having the following characteristics:

    1) They are very active in social media and create reviews around new products.

    2) They have a reasonable high social status and access to finances.

    3) They have high levels of education and a reasonable approach to risk.

    4) They have a degree of "thought leadearship" for other potential adopters.

    All those facts combined help to a rapid adoption of alternatives as this one in which technology and a healthy alternative of transportation are involved. The next chart is a generalization of the adoption curve that exist with technology.

ax1.set_ylabel("Gender", fontsize=16)

ax2.set_title("Customers by gender", fontsize=20)

    Text(0, 0.5, 'Gender')

    The previous charts show some interesting information. The first thing is that in the case of subscribers the uses of women are less than 30% in comparison with the men. However, for the customers the participation is a bit higher getting close to a 50%.

    Another point is that in the case of customers is more common to not proportionate the information about its gender. This fact can be analyzed for the UX designers and validate if there exist an alternative to improve the process and capture this information. Likewise, the category "Not defined" was introduced as the treatment for the NaN values. This is important to denote because could help to identify if those cases were produce for an error of the system or a period of time where the app does not require to define a gender in order to use its services.
